-- ============================================================
-- ENTRY 1: RuVector WASM: Complete Vector Database in the Browser
-- ============================================================
INSERT INTO ask_ruvnet.kb_complete (file_path, title, content, category, quality_score, chunk_count, original_chars)
VALUES (
  'kb/ruvector-wasm-browser.md',
  'RuVector WASM: Complete Vector Database in the Browser (<400KB)',
  E'# RuVector WASM: Complete Vector Database in the Browser (<400KB)\n\nA full vector database running entirely in your web browser, with no server required. RuVector compiles to WebAssembly (WASM) and ships as a single module under 400KB, enabling offline-first semantic search on any device with a modern browser.\n\n---\n\n## Why a Vector Database in the Browser?\n\nTraditional vector search requires a server: your app sends a query, the server runs the search, and returns results. This works, but it introduces latency, requires infrastructure, and sends user data over the network.\n\nRuVector WASM eliminates all three problems:\n\n```\nTRADITIONAL ARCHITECTURE              RUVECTOR WASM ARCHITECTURE\n=====================                 ========================\n\n+--------+     +--------+             +---------------------------+\n| Browser | --> | Server |             |         Browser           |\n|         |     |        |             |                           |\n| Query:  |     | Vector |             |  +---------+ +---------+ |\n| "cats"  | --> | DB     |             |  | Query:  | | WASM    | |\n|         |     |        |             |  | "cats"  |-| Vector  | |\n|         | <-- | Result |             |  |         | | DB      | |\n+--------+     +--------+             |  +---------+ +---------+ |\n    |               |                  |       Results: instant    |\n    +-- Network --+                    +---------------------------+\n    Latency: 50-200ms                      Latency: <10ms\n    Privacy: data leaves device            Privacy: data stays local\n    Offline: breaks                        Offline: works\n```\n\n---\n\n## Micro-HNSW: The 7.2KB Neuromorphic Core\n\nAt the heart of RuVector WASM is Micro-HNSW, a 7.2KB WebAssembly module that implements Hierarchical Navigable Small World graphs using a neuromorphic architecture inspired by spiking neural networks.\n\n### How it works:\n\n1. **Spiking neurons** represent graph nodes. Each vector is a neuron.\n2. **Spike propagation** replaces traditional graph traversal. When you search, the query vector \"fires\" and activates nearby neurons.\n3. **Lateral inhibition** prunes distant candidates, focusing the search on the most promising region.\n4. **Multi-layer hierarchy** enables logarithmic search time (O(log n) instead of O(n)).\n\n```\nHNSW Layer Structure (4 layers)\n================================\n\nLayer 3 (sparse):    [A]--------[D]           <- Long-range links\n                      |          |\nLayer 2:         [A]--[B]--[C]--[D]           <- Medium-range links\n                  |    |    |    |\nLayer 1:     [A]-[B]-[C]-[D]-[E]-[F]         <- Short-range links\n              |   |   |   |   |   |\nLayer 0:  [A][B][C][D][E][F][G][H][I][J]     <- All vectors (ground truth)\n\nSearch path for query Q near E:\n  Layer 3: Start at A -> jump to D\n  Layer 2: D -> C (closer to E)\n  Layer 1: C -> D -> E (found!)\n  Layer 0: Refine among E''s neighbors\n```\n\nThe result: search across 1,000 vectors completes in under 10 milliseconds. At 10,000 vectors, typical search time is 25-40ms -- fast enough for real-time typeahead.\n\n---\n\n## Scalar Quantization: 4x Compression, 0.9999 Quality\n\nRaw embedding vectors use 32-bit floats. A single 384-dimensional vector occupies 1,536 bytes. For 1,000 vectors, that is 1.5MB before indexing overhead.\n\nScalar quantization (SQ8) converts each float to an 8-bit integer, cutting storage to 384 bytes per vector -- a 4x reduction.\n\n```\nOriginal (f32):    [0.0234, -0.1567, 0.8921, ...]   1,536 bytes\n                         |\n                   Quantize: map [min, max] -> [0, 255]\n                         |\nQuantized (u8):    [134, 23, 241, ...]               384 bytes\n\nCosine similarity between original and quantized: 0.9999\n(Virtually lossless -- the difference is unmeasurable in practice)\n```\n\nRuVector stores quantization parameters (min/max per dimension) in a small sidecar file (~2.6KB), enabling exact dequantization when needed.\n\n---\n\n## Transformers.js Integration: Embeddings Without a Server\n\nTo search vectors, you first need to create them. RuVector WASM pairs with Transformers.js to run the all-MiniLM-L6-v2 embedding model directly in the browser:\n\n- **Model size**: 22MB ONNX (downloaded once, cached by browser)\n- **Dimensions**: 384 (matches RuVector''s SQ8 format)\n- **Speed**: ~15ms per sentence on modern hardware\n- **Privacy**: Text never leaves the device\n\n---\n\n## Complete Code Example: Browser Vector Search\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<head><title>RuVector Browser Search</title></head>\n<body>\n<script type=\"module\">\nimport { pipeline } from ''https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@xenova/transformers'';\nimport { RvfStore } from ''/assets/rvf-engine.js'';\n\n// 1. Load the embedding model (cached after first load)\nconst embedder = await pipeline(''feature-extraction'', ''Xenova/all-MiniLM-L6-v2'');\n\n// 2. Load the RVF knowledge base\nconst store = new RvfStore();\nawait store.load(''/assets/knowledge.rvf'');\n\n// 3. Search function\nasync function search(query) {\n  // Generate query embedding (384 dimensions)\n  const output = await embedder(query, { pooling: ''mean'', normalize: true });\n  const queryVector = Array.from(output.data);\n\n  // Search the RVF store (returns top 5 matches)\n  const results = store.search(queryVector, { limit: 5 });\n\n  results.forEach(r => {\n    console.log(`Score: ${r.score.toFixed(4)} | ${r.title}`);\n  });\n}\n\n// 4. Try it\nawait search(''How do vector databases work?'');\n// Score: 0.8923 | RuVector Architecture: HNSW Indexing Deep Dive\n// Score: 0.8541 | What Are Embeddings and Why They Matter\n// Score: 0.8102 | Scalar Quantization: Compressing Vectors\n</script>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n---\n\n## Use Cases\n\n| Use Case | Why WASM? |\n|----------|----------|\n| **Offline-first apps** | Search works without internet after initial load |\n| **Privacy-sensitive search** | Medical, legal, or personal data never leaves the device |\n| **Edge devices** | Raspberry Pi, kiosks, IoT with a browser |\n| **Low-latency UX** | No network round-trip means instant results |\n| **Cost reduction** | No server infrastructure for search |\n| **Progressive web apps** | Full functionality with Service Worker caching |\n\n---\n\n## Size Budget\n\n```\nComponent                    Size (gzipped)\n-------------------------------------------\nMicro-HNSW WASM module       7.2 KB\nRVF runtime (JS)            12.4 KB\nSQ8 dequantizer              3.1 KB\n-------------------------------------------\nTotal engine                 22.7 KB\n\nKnowledge base (353 entries) 507 KB (knowledge.rvf)\nContent sidecar              474 KB (content-sidecar.json.gz)\nEmbedding model (optional)    22 MB (all-MiniLM-L6-v2, cached)\n```\n\nThe core engine is 22.7KB. The knowledge base scales with your content. The embedding model is only needed if you generate new embeddings in the browser -- if you pre-compute embeddings at build time, skip it entirely.\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nRuVector WASM proves that vector search does not need a server. A 7.2KB neuromorphic WASM module, combined with scalar quantization and Transformers.js, delivers sub-10ms semantic search entirely in the browser. For applications where privacy, latency, or offline capability matter, this architecture eliminates the server from the equation entirely.',
  'wasm-local-llm',
  98,
  1,
  5200
);

-- ============================================================
-- ENTRY 2: Swarm Topologies Explained: When to Use Each Pattern
-- ============================================================
INSERT INTO ask_ruvnet.kb_complete (file_path, title, content, category, quality_score, chunk_count, original_chars)
VALUES (
  'kb/swarm-topologies-explained.md',
  'Swarm Topologies Explained: When to Use Each Pattern',
  E'# Swarm Topologies Explained: When to Use Each Pattern\n\nWhen you run multiple AI agents together, the way they communicate determines everything: speed, reliability, cost, and whether the result is coherent or a mess. Ruflo supports six swarm topologies. This guide explains each one, when to use it, and what can go wrong.\n\n---\n\n## The Six Topologies at a Glance\n\n```\n1. HIERARCHICAL           2. HIERARCHICAL-MESH        3. MESH\n\n      [Queen]                   [Queen]              [A]---[B]\n     /   |   \\                 /   |   \\             | \\   / |\n   [W1] [W2] [W3]           [W1]-[W2]-[W3]          |  [C]  |\n                              \\   |   /              | /   \\ |\n   Queen controls all.        Queen + peer chat.     [D]---[E]\n   Workers never talk         Workers share info     Everyone talks\n   to each other.             AND report to queen.   to everyone.\n\n4. RING                   5. STAR                    6. ADAPTIVE\n\n   [A] -> [B]                  [C1]                  Switches between\n    ^      |                  / | \\                  topologies based\n    |      v                [W1][W2][W3]             on load and task.\n   [D] <- [C]                                       Starts hierarchical,\n                             Central coordinator.    may shift to mesh\n   Each agent passes          Simple but fragile.    under pressure.\n   to the next in line.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 1. Hierarchical Topology\n\n**Structure**: One queen agent controls all worker agents. Workers report only to the queen and never communicate with each other.\n\n**Best for**: 6-8 agents, tightly controlled tasks, predictable workflows.\n\n```\nQueen assigns tasks:\n  Queen -> Worker 1: \"Write the API endpoint\"\n  Queen -> Worker 2: \"Write the database schema\"\n  Queen -> Worker 3: \"Write the tests\"\n\nWorkers report back:\n  Worker 1 -> Queen: \"API endpoint complete\"\n  Worker 2 -> Queen: \"Schema complete\"\n  Worker 3 -> Queen: \"Tests complete\"\n\nQueen synthesizes:\n  Queen: \"All components done. Integrating...\"\n```\n\n**Strengths**: Maximum control, anti-drift (queen catches inconsistencies), clear accountability.\n\n**Weaknesses**: Queen is a bottleneck. If she falls behind, all workers stall. Communication overhead scales as O(n) with the queen handling every message.\n\n**Anti-drift mechanism**: The queen periodically reviews worker output and issues corrections. Workers cannot deviate without the queen noticing on the next check-in cycle.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Hierarchical-Mesh Topology (V3)\n\n**Structure**: A queen controls workers, but workers can also communicate with each other. This is the V3 evolution of pure hierarchical.\n\n**Best for**: 10-15 agents, complex tasks where workers need to coordinate.\n\n```\n         [Queen]\n        /   |   \\\n      [W1]-[W2]-[W3]\n        \\   |   /\n         [W4]\n\nQueen assigns high-level goals.\nWorkers coordinate details peer-to-peer.\nQueen intervenes only when workers disagree.\n```\n\n**Why it exists**: Pure hierarchical breaks down above 8 agents because the queen becomes a bottleneck. Hierarchical-mesh lets workers resolve simple coordination directly (\"Hey W2, what format is your API response?\") while the queen focuses on strategy and conflict resolution.\n\n**Strengths**: Scales better than pure hierarchical. Reduces queen load by 40-60%. Workers resolve dependencies faster.\n\n**Weaknesses**: More complex to debug. Potential for workers to agree on something wrong without queen oversight.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Mesh Topology\n\n**Structure**: Every agent connects to every other agent. No central authority.\n\n**Best for**: Creative tasks, brainstorming, exploration where you want maximum cross-pollination.\n\n```\nConnections in a 5-agent mesh: 10 edges\nConnections in a 10-agent mesh: 45 edges\nConnections in a 20-agent mesh: 190 edges  <-- Communication explosion\n\nFormula: n(n-1)/2 edges\n```\n\n**Strengths**: Maximum flexibility and information sharing. No single point of failure. Any agent can pick up where another left off.\n\n**Weaknesses**: Drift risk is highest here. Without a queen, agents may gradually diverge in approach, style, or even goals. Communication overhead grows quadratically. Not recommended above 8 agents.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Ring Topology\n\n**Structure**: Agents form a circle. Each agent receives input from the previous agent and passes output to the next.\n\n**Best for**: Pipeline processing, sequential transformation, document review chains.\n\n```\nDocument Review Pipeline:\n\n  [Drafter] -> [Fact-Checker] -> [Editor] -> [Formatter]\n      ^                                          |\n      +------ Feedback loop (optional) ----------+\n\nEach agent transforms and passes forward.\n```\n\n**Strengths**: Clear data flow, each agent has a well-defined role, easy to reason about, low communication overhead (O(n)).\n\n**Weaknesses**: Latency is the sum of all agents. If one agent is slow, the entire pipeline stalls. A failure in any single agent breaks the chain.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Star Topology\n\n**Structure**: One central coordinator connects to all agents, but agents do not connect to each other. Similar to hierarchical, but the coordinator routes messages rather than commanding.\n\n**Best for**: Simple fan-out tasks, parallel independent work, aggregation.\n\n```\n          [Coordinator]\n         / |    |    \\\n       [A] [B] [C]  [D]\n\nCoordinator: \"Everyone search your assigned topic\"\nA, B, C, D work independently.\nCoordinator: \"Combine all results into final report\"\n```\n\n**Strengths**: Simple to implement, good for embarrassingly parallel tasks, easy to add/remove agents.\n\n**Weaknesses**: Coordinator is a single point of failure. If it crashes, all agents are orphaned. No agent-to-agent communication means duplicated work is possible.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Adaptive Topology\n\n**Structure**: Starts with one topology and dynamically switches based on load, task complexity, and agent health.\n\n**Best for**: Long-running tasks, unpredictable workloads, production systems.\n\n```\nPhase 1 (Planning):     Hierarchical  -- Queen plans, assigns\nPhase 2 (Execution):    Mesh          -- Workers collaborate freely\nPhase 3 (Integration):  Star          -- Coordinator collects results\nPhase 4 (Review):       Ring          -- Sequential quality checks\n```\n\n**Strengths**: Optimizes for each phase of work. Can self-heal by switching away from a failing topology.\n\n**Weaknesses**: Most complex to configure. Requires monitoring to trigger topology changes. Debugging is harder when the shape keeps changing.\n\n---\n\n## Decision Framework\n\n```\nDecision Tree: Choosing Your Topology\n=====================================\n\nHow many agents?\n  |\n  +-- 2-5 agents\n  |     |\n  |     +-- Pipeline task? -> RING\n  |     +-- Independent tasks? -> STAR\n  |     +-- Collaborative? -> MESH\n  |\n  +-- 6-8 agents\n  |     |\n  |     +-- Need tight control? -> HIERARCHICAL\n  |     +-- Need creativity? -> MESH (with drift monitoring)\n  |\n  +-- 9-15 agents\n  |     |\n  |     +-- Structured task? -> HIERARCHICAL-MESH\n  |     +-- Dynamic workload? -> ADAPTIVE\n  |\n  +-- 16+ agents\n        |\n        +-- ADAPTIVE (mandatory at this scale)\n        +-- Or partition into multiple smaller swarms\n```\n\n---\n\n## Ruflo CLI Examples\n\n```bash\n# Spawn a hierarchical swarm with 6 workers\nnpx ruflo@latest swarm init --topology hierarchical --agents 6\n\n# Spawn a mesh for brainstorming\nnpx ruflo@latest swarm init --topology mesh --agents 4\n\n# Spawn adaptive for a long-running build\nnpx ruflo@latest swarm init --topology adaptive --agents 10\n\n# Check current topology and agent health\nnpx ruflo@latest swarm status\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nTopology is not a cosmetic choice -- it determines whether your agents cooperate or collide. Start with hierarchical for control, graduate to hierarchical-mesh for scale, and use adaptive when you need the system to optimize itself. Never run more than 8 agents in a pure mesh unless you have drift monitoring in place.',
  'swarms',
  98,
  1,
  5800
);

-- ============================================================
-- ENTRY 3: MinCut Analysis: Finding Bottlenecks, Weak Points, and Knowledge Gaps
-- ============================================================
INSERT INTO ask_ruvnet.kb_complete (file_path, title, content, category, quality_score, chunk_count, original_chars)
VALUES (
  'kb/mincut-analysis-guide.md',
  'MinCut Analysis: Finding Bottlenecks, Weak Points, and Knowledge Gaps',
  E'# MinCut Analysis: Finding Bottlenecks, Weak Points, and Knowledge Gaps\n\nMinCut is a graph algorithm that answers one deceptively powerful question: \"What is the smallest set of connections I need to cut to split this system in two?\" That question reveals bottlenecks in code, attack surfaces in security, gaps in knowledge bases, and single points of failure in distributed systems.\n\n---\n\n## What MinCut Actually Does\n\nGiven a graph (nodes connected by edges), the minimum cut finds the fewest edges whose removal disconnects the graph into two separate components.\n\n```\nBEFORE MinCut                        AFTER MinCut (cut 2 edges)\n===========                          ===========\n\n[A]--[B]--[C]                        [A]--[B]  |  [C]\n |    |    |                          |    |    |   |\n[D]--[E]--[F]                        [D]--[E]  |  [F]\n      |    |                               |   |   |\n     [G]--[H]                             [G]  |  [H]\n                                               |\n                                          Cut edges:\n                                          B--C and E--F\n\nMinCut value: 2 (only 2 edges need cutting)\nThis means B-C and E-F are the BOTTLENECK\nconnecting the left and right halves.\n```\n\nThe smaller the MinCut value, the more fragile that connection is. A MinCut of 1 means a single edge failure splits the system.\n\n---\n\n## Application 1: Code Architecture\n\nTreat your codebase as a graph where modules are nodes and imports/dependencies are edges. MinCut reveals the natural module boundaries and the tightest coupling points.\n\n```\nModule Dependency Graph:\n\n[auth]----+\n  |       |\n  v       v\n[users]->[api]->[database]\n  |       |\n  v       v\n[roles]->[cache]\n\nMinCut between [auth] and [database]: 1 (through [api])\nThis means: [api] is a bottleneck. If api fails,\nauth cannot reach the database at all.\n\nMinCut between [users] and [cache]: 2 (through [api] and direct)\nThis means: Better resilience. Two independent paths exist.\n```\n\n**What to do with this information:**\n- MinCut of 1 between critical modules: Add a redundant path or decouple.\n- MinCut identifies the natural seam for splitting a monolith into microservices.\n- High MinCut between modules means they are tightly coupled -- consider whether that coupling is intentional.\n\n---\n\n## Application 2: Security Attack Surface\n\nIn security, MinCut identifies the minimum number of defenses an attacker must breach to reach a target. Lower MinCut = higher risk.\n\n```\nNetwork Security Graph:\n\n[Internet]--[Firewall]--[DMZ]--[App Server]--[Database]\n                |                    |\n            [WAF]--[Load Balancer]--+\n\nMinCut from [Internet] to [Database]: 2\n  Path 1: Firewall -> DMZ -> App Server -> Database\n  Path 2: WAF -> Load Balancer -> App Server -> Database\n  Bottleneck: App Server (both paths converge here)\n\nSecurity insight: App Server is the critical chokepoint.\nIf compromised, the database is one hop away regardless\nof which outer defense was breached.\n```\n\n**What to do with this information:**\n- Low MinCut to sensitive assets: Add defense layers.\n- Converging paths: The convergence node needs the strongest hardening.\n- MinCut of 1 anywhere in a security graph is a red flag.\n\n---\n\n## Application 3: Knowledge Base Gap Detection\n\nIn a knowledge graph, topics are nodes and references between them are edges. MinCut reveals poorly connected knowledge areas -- gaps where one missing article could isolate an entire topic.\n\n```\nKnowledge Graph:\n\n[Embeddings]--[Vector Search]--[HNSW]\n      |              |            |\n[Transformers]   [Cosine Sim]  [Graphs]\n      |              |\n[Attention]----[Tokenization]\n\nMinCut between [Embeddings] cluster and [HNSW] cluster: 1\n  Only connection: [Vector Search]\n\nGap identified: If the \"Vector Search\" article were removed,\nthe reader would have no bridge from understanding embeddings\nto understanding HNSW indexing. Need more cross-references.\n```\n\n**What to do with this information:**\n- MinCut of 1 between topic clusters: Write bridging content.\n- Isolated nodes (MinCut of 0): Orphan articles that need links.\n- High MinCut between clusters: Well-connected knowledge area.\n\n---\n\n## Application 4: Swarm Resilience\n\nIn a Ruflo swarm, agents are nodes and communication channels are edges. MinCut tells you how many agents can fail before the swarm splits into disconnected groups.\n\n```\nHierarchical Swarm:              Mesh Swarm (5 agents):\n\n      [Queen]                    [A]---[B]\n     /   |   \\                   | \\   / |\n   [W1] [W2] [W3]               |  [C]  |\n                                 | /   \\ |\n   MinCut: 1                     [D]---[E]\n   (Remove Queen = total\n    disconnection)               MinCut: 2\n                                 (Must remove 2 agents to\n                                  split the group)\n```\n\n**Key insight**: Hierarchical topologies always have MinCut = 1 (the queen). This is why hierarchical-mesh exists -- adding peer connections between workers raises the MinCut above 1.\n\n---\n\n## RuVector Implementation\n\nRuVector provides MinCut analysis through the graph-analyzer module:\n\n```javascript\nimport { analyzeGraph, analyzeMinCutBoundaries } from ''@ruvector/graph-analyzer'';\n\n// Build a graph from your system\nconst graph = {\n  nodes: [''auth'', ''api'', ''database'', ''cache'', ''users''],\n  edges: [\n    { from: ''auth'', to: ''api'', weight: 1 },\n    { from: ''api'', to: ''database'', weight: 1 },\n    { from: ''api'', to: ''cache'', weight: 1 },\n    { from: ''users'', to: ''api'', weight: 1 },\n    { from: ''users'', to: ''database'', weight: 1 },\n  ]\n};\n\n// Find MinCut between two nodes\nconst result = analyzeGraph(graph, { source: ''auth'', target: ''database'' });\nconsole.log(`MinCut value: ${result.minCutValue}`);  // 1\nconsole.log(`Cut edges:`, result.cutEdges);           // [{auth -> api}]\n\n// Find ALL natural boundaries in the graph\nconst boundaries = analyzeMinCutBoundaries(graph);\nboundaries.forEach(b => {\n  console.log(`Boundary: ${b.partition1} | ${b.partition2}`);\n  console.log(`  Strength: ${b.minCutValue}`);\n  console.log(`  Bottleneck edges: ${b.cutEdges.length}`);\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Louvain Community Detection: The Complement to MinCut\n\nWhile MinCut finds where to cut, Louvain community detection finds natural clusters -- groups of nodes that are more connected to each other than to the rest of the graph.\n\n```\nLouvain on a codebase graph might find:\n\n  Community 1: [auth, users, roles, permissions]     <- \"Identity\" module\n  Community 2: [api, routes, middleware, validators]  <- \"HTTP\" module\n  Community 3: [database, cache, migrations, seeds]   <- \"Data\" module\n\nThese communities suggest natural microservice boundaries.\nMinCut between communities tells you how coupled they are.\n```\n\nUse both together: Louvain tells you WHAT the natural groups are. MinCut tells you HOW STRONG the boundaries between them are.\n\n---\n\n## Dynamic MinCut for Real-Time Health Monitoring\n\nIn production systems, MinCut can be recalculated continuously as edges appear and disappear (services going up and down):\n\n```\nTime 0:  MinCut = 3  (healthy -- 3 redundant paths)\nTime 1:  MinCut = 2  (service C went down -- still okay)\nTime 2:  MinCut = 1  (service D went down -- WARNING)\nTime 3:  MinCut = 0  (service E went down -- SPLIT! System partitioned)\n\nAlert thresholds:\n  MinCut >= 3: Green (resilient)\n  MinCut == 2: Yellow (degraded)\n  MinCut == 1: Red (critical -- one failure from partition)\n  MinCut == 0: Black (system split, data inconsistency risk)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nMinCut is not just a graph theory exercise. It is a practical diagnostic tool that reveals the weakest points in any connected system -- code, networks, knowledge, or agent swarms. When the MinCut value is low, that connection is fragile and deserves attention. When it is high, the system is resilient. Run MinCut analysis on anything you build, and fix the weak points before they break.',
  'algorithms',
  98,
  1,
  5700
);

-- ============================================================
-- ENTRY 4: Hyperbolic Embeddings: Why Flat Space Isn't Enough for AI
-- ============================================================
INSERT INTO ask_ruvnet.kb_complete (file_path, title, content, category, quality_score, chunk_count, original_chars)
VALUES (
  'kb/hyperbolic-embeddings-guide.md',
  'Hyperbolic Embeddings: Why Flat Space Is Not Enough for AI',
  E'# Hyperbolic Embeddings: Why Flat Space Is Not Enough for AI\n\nStandard AI embeddings place concepts in Euclidean (flat) space. This works well for uniform data, but it fundamentally distorts hierarchical relationships. Hyperbolic embeddings solve this by placing data in curved space where hierarchies are natural, not forced.\n\n---\n\n## The Problem with Flat Space\n\nImagine mapping a corporate org chart into 2D coordinates. The CEO is at the top, VPs below, directors below them, and individual contributors at the bottom. In Euclidean space, every level gets the same amount of room:\n\n```\nEUCLIDEAN (FLAT) SPACE                REALITY\n==================                     =======\n\n      [CEO]                            1 person at top\n     /     \\                           |\n  [VP1]   [VP2]                        4 VPs\n  / \\      / \\                         |\n[D1][D2] [D3][D4]                      16 Directors\n                                       |\n(Where do 200 ICs fit??)               200 ICs\n\nProblem: Bottom level has 200 people\nbut the same spatial \"width\" as the\ntop level with 1 person.\n\nResult: ICs get CRUSHED together.\nSimilar ICs become indistinguishable.\nDistances become meaningless.\n```\n\nIn Euclidean space, the circumference of a circle grows linearly with radius (C = 2 * pi * r). But hierarchies grow **exponentially** -- each level has many more nodes than the level above. Flat space cannot represent this without distortion.\n\n---\n\n## Hyperbolic Space: Exponential Room at the Edges\n\nIn hyperbolic space, the \"circumference\" grows exponentially with radius. This means the further from the center you go, the more room there is -- exactly matching the growth pattern of hierarchies.\n\n```\nPOINCARE BALL MODEL (2D projection of hyperbolic space)\n======================================================\n\n                    +------ Boundary (infinity) ------+\n                   /                                   \\\n                  /     .  .  .  .  .  .  .  .          \\\n                 /   .  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  .        \\\n                |  .  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  .       |\n                | .                                 .     |\n                |   .  Dir  Dir  Dir  Dir  Dir  .         |\n                |      .                       .          |\n                |         .  VP    VP   .                  |\n                |              .     .                    |\n                |                CEO                     |\n                |              .     .                    |\n                |         .  VP    VP   .                  |\n                |      .                       .          |\n                |   .  Dir  Dir  Dir  Dir  Dir  .         |\n                | .                                 .     |\n                |  .  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  .       |\n                 \\   .  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  IC  .        /\n                  \\     .  .  .  .  .  .  .  .          /\n                   \\                                   /\n                    +----------------------------------+\n\n  Center: CEO (root of hierarchy)\n  Middle ring: VPs and Directors (intermediate levels)\n  Outer area: Individual contributors (leaves)\n\n  Key insight: The outer ring has EXPONENTIALLY more room\n  than the center, perfectly fitting the 200 ICs without\n  crushing them together.\n```\n\nThe Poincare ball maps infinite hyperbolic space into a finite disk. Distances near the boundary are much larger than they appear -- two points that look close near the edge are actually very far apart in hyperbolic distance.\n\n---\n\n## When Hyperbolic Embeddings Outperform Euclidean\n\n### Data with natural hierarchies (USE hyperbolic):\n\n- **Taxonomies**: Species classification (Kingdom > Phylum > Class > Order > ...)\n- **Org charts**: Companies, military chains of command\n- **File systems**: Directories and subdirectories\n- **Ontologies**: Medical terminology (Body > System > Organ > Tissue > Cell)\n- **Knowledge graphs**: Wikipedia categories, concept hierarchies\n- **Language**: WordNet hypernym trees (animal > mammal > dog > poodle)\n\n### Flat/uniform data (KEEP Euclidean):\n\n- **Sentiment analysis**: Positive/negative is a spectrum, not a tree\n- **Color similarity**: Colors live on a relatively flat manifold\n- **Simple document search**: Most document collections are not hierarchical\n- **Image features**: CNN features are typically well-served by cosine similarity\n\n---\n\n## The Math: Cosine Similarity vs Hyperbolic Distance\n\n```\nEUCLIDEAN COSINE SIMILARITY:\n  sim(a, b) = (a . b) / (||a|| * ||b||)\n  Range: [-1, 1]\n  Measures: angle between vectors\n  Hierarchy-aware: NO\n\nHYPERBOLIC DISTANCE (Poincare ball):\n  d(a, b) = arcosh(1 + 2 * ||a - b||^2 / ((1 - ||a||^2)(1 - ||b||^2)))\n  Range: [0, infinity)\n  Measures: geodesic distance on curved manifold\n  Hierarchy-aware: YES\n\nKey difference:\n  In cosine similarity, \"dog\" and \"cat\" might be as similar\n  as \"dog\" and \"animal\" -- both are close in angle.\n\n  In hyperbolic distance, \"dog\" is CLOSER to \"animal\" (parent)\n  than to \"cat\" (sibling at same level), because the parent-child\n  relationship is encoded in the radial dimension.\n```\n\n---\n\n## RuVector''s Hyperbolic Implementation\n\nRuVector implements hyperbolic search using the Lorentz (hyperboloid) model internally, which is numerically more stable than the Poincare ball for gradient computations, then projects to Poincare for visualization.\n\n```javascript\n// RuVector hyperbolic embedding example\nimport { HyperbolicHNSW } from ''@ruvector/hyperbolic'';\n\nconst index = new HyperbolicHNSW({\n  dimensions: 64,      // Hyperbolic embeddings are effective at lower dims\n  curvature: -1.0,     // Negative curvature = hyperbolic space\n  model: ''lorentz'',    // Lorentz model for numerical stability\n});\n\n// Add hierarchical data\nindex.add(''animal'',  embedTaxonomy(''animal''));   // Near center\nindex.add(''mammal'',  embedTaxonomy(''mammal''));   // Middle ring\nindex.add(''dog'',     embedTaxonomy(''dog''));      // Outer ring\nindex.add(''poodle'',  embedTaxonomy(''poodle''));   // Near boundary\nindex.add(''cat'',     embedTaxonomy(''cat''));      // Outer ring\n\n// Search respects hierarchy\nconst results = index.search(embedTaxonomy(''canine''), { limit: 3 });\n// 1. dog     (same branch, closest)\n// 2. poodle  (child of dog, same branch)\n// 3. mammal  (parent, same lineage)\n// NOT cat (sibling branch -- further in hyperbolic space)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Dimension Efficiency: Hyperbolic Needs Fewer Dimensions\n\nOne practical advantage: hyperbolic embeddings achieve the same representational quality in far fewer dimensions than Euclidean.\n\n```\nTree with 10,000 nodes, 15 levels deep:\n\n  Euclidean embeddings:  384 dimensions needed for 95% accuracy\n  Hyperbolic embeddings:  64 dimensions needed for 95% accuracy\n\n  Storage savings: 6x\n  Search speed improvement: ~4x (fewer dimensions = faster distance calc)\n```\n\nThis is because the exponential growth of hyperbolic space provides \"free\" capacity that Euclidean space must compensate for with extra dimensions.\n\n---\n\n## Comparison Table\n\n| Property | Euclidean (Cosine) | Hyperbolic (Poincare/Lorentz) |\n|----------|-------------------|-------------------------------|\n| Best for | Flat, uniform data | Hierarchical, tree-like data |\n| Dimensions needed | High (128-768) | Low (32-128) |\n| Hierarchy encoding | No (implicit only) | Yes (radial = depth) |\n| Computation cost | Low (dot product) | Medium (arcosh, norms) |\n| Library support | Universal | Specialized (RuVector, gensim) |\n| Visualization | Straightforward | Requires Poincare projection |\n| Training stability | High | Requires careful optimization |\n\n---\n\n## Decision Framework\n\n```\nIs your data naturally hierarchical?\n  |\n  +-- YES: Does it have 5+ levels of depth?\n  |     |\n  |     +-- YES -> Hyperbolic embeddings (significant gains)\n  |     +-- NO  -> Test both; hyperbolic may not justify complexity\n  |\n  +-- NO: Is your data a flat collection of similar items?\n        |\n        +-- YES -> Euclidean cosine similarity (simpler, proven)\n        +-- NO  -> Consider hybrid: Euclidean for similarity,\n                   hyperbolic for hierarchical relationships\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nEuclidean space is flat. Hierarchies are not. When you force tree-structured data into flat embeddings, the leaves get crushed together and parent-child relationships become invisible. Hyperbolic embeddings solve this by providing exponentially more room at the edges, matching the natural growth pattern of hierarchies. Use them when your data has depth -- taxonomies, org charts, file systems, ontologies. Keep Euclidean when your data is genuinely flat.',
